<TEXT>
czechoslovak police broke up a meeting of 
the charter 77 human rights group after members passed a resolution 
backing democratic reform in the soviet bloc an emigre source 
reported sunday 
the group also has called for a probe into the death of a 
humanrights activist and into the czech judiciary the source said 
the meeting in a prague restaurant was attended saturday by at 
least 50 charter 77 signatories according to palach press a 
londonbased newsletter monitoring developments in czechoslovakia 
it said police raided the restaurant and seized many of those 
present 
all those detained were released later in the day after many 
hours of interrogation about charter 77 activities the report 
said 
the charter 77 resolution praised the creation of two 
independent groups in czechoslovakia in the past month to deal with 
the issues of peace social welfare and trade union rights 
it also said recent strikes in poland creation of the network 
of free initiatives in hungary and the foundation of the democratic 
union in the soviet union clearly shows that the need for 
political and trade union freedoms is being felt ever more acutely 
in the sovietbloc countries 
the network of free initiatives an umbrella organization was 
formed early this month in budapest after a petition calling for a 
multiparty parliamentary democracy in hungary was circulated in 
april 
the democratic union which was founded in moscow recently seeks 
a new constitution and the withdrawal of soviet troops from eastern 
europe and areas of the soviet union seized in world war ii 
in a recently released document charter 77 claimed that 
activist pavel wonka who died in a prison at hradec kralove on 
april 26 suffered mistreatment during a previous 21month prison 
term 
wonka was rearrested because he refused to comply with strict 
protective surveillance rules and sentenced to another 
fivemonth term carter 77 said and he died five days later 
the document called for an independent investigation and also an 
independent probe of the overall state of the judiciary and prison 
systems 
</TEXT>
