<TEXT>
vermont lawmakers approved controversial 
legislation saturday designed to preserve open land and give the 
state more control over development 
the socalled growth bill topped the legislative agenda for 
gov madeleine kunin and democrats who control both the house and 
senate its passage was expected to pave the way to the 
legislatures adjournment for the year originally targeted for 
midapril 
a conference committees compromise version of the proposal was 
approved by the senate 1713 and the house 7765 that sealed the 
success of a shaky coalition of lawmakers who favored more support 
for vermonts farmers and those who favored stronger development 
planning 
if ever there was a team effort this bill was it said rep 
stephen reynes a democrat and strong backer of the growth 
legislation 
the growth bill was the legislatures response to a report 
produced by a special governors commission on vermonts future 
formed last year and headed by vermont law school dean douglas 
costle 
the bill provides 75 million in direct subsidies to dairy 
farmers for one year a 50cent per hundredweight offsetting of a 
recent federal milk price support cut of the same size 
if dairy farmers want relief next year they must join other 
farmers in signing up for an abatement program that will pay most 
of their property taxes in exchange for a promise not to sell out 
to developers 
with backers of the growth bill citing sharply rising real 
estate prices as another of developments dangers the legislature 
set aside about a third of this years surplus 20 million for 
the housing and land conservation trust fund 
the fund is designed to help provide affordable housing by 
enabling tenants to buy their apartment complexes and through other 
means it also is to be used to buy development rights on valuable 
open land 
a third part of the growth bill calls for stronger local 
regional and state planning kunin introduced it in her state of 
the state address in january by asking that may be changed to 
shall in several passages of state law on planning 
in the compromise the planning sections will not take effect 
for a year to give time for bugs to be worked out 
</TEXT>
