the term zero tolerance originated last year when us 
attorney peter nunez of san diego calif and us customs service 
agents began arresting motorists carrying even tiny amounts of 
drugs across the border the customs agents and nunez were 
embarking on an effort that has become a model for the federal 
governments current war on drug users 
under the san diego operation an average of 15 people a week 
are charged with drug possession many of whom are firsttime 
offenders who wind up on probation for one year 
i encourage federal prosecutors nationwide to emulate the 
program in san diego with all available prosecution resources 
attorney general edwin meese iii said in a march 30 memo to all 
us attorneys 
meese noted that the antidrug abuse act of 1986 includes a 
1000 mandatory minimum fine for possession and that federal civil 
asset forfeiture provisions permit law enforcement officers to 
confiscate any vehicle carrying drugs even in trace amounts 
when used judiciously meese said in the memo these 
sanctions send present and potential users a clear signal about the 
unacceptability of drug use 
the reagan administrations view is that possession is a very 
serious thing and that its the possession of the drug which needs 
to be dealt with if were ever going to address with the drug 
problem in a serious way said justice department spokesman terry 
eastland what puts bite into our entire user prosecution 
initiative is this forfeiture aspect 
drug traffickers frequently are the target of asset forfeiture 
proceedings while users seldom have been but under federal law on 
civil asset forfeiture there is no distinction between the 
property of drug users and drug traffickers forfeiture does not 
depend on the quantity of drugs involved nor is it a legal defense 
under the forfeiture law to claim that the contraband was intended 
for personal use rather than commercial trafficking 
meese noted in his march 30 memo that our primary narcotics 
enforcement focus at the federal level has been and will continue 
to be on supply reduction 
but it is becoming increasingly apparent that a more 
consistent enforcement presence on the demand side is vital to the 
success of our national antidrug program meese said in the memo 
