<TEXT>
chinas government concerned about its growing 
foreign debt is setting up a debt management office to ensure that 
borrowing does not exceed its ability to pay an official report 
said sunday 
the englishlanguage newspaper china daily said the state 
council chinas cabinet is expected to approve plans to establish 
the office in the ministry of finance according to an unidentified 
source in the ministry 
it said the department will supervise all of chinas foreign 
and domestic debts and set up a buffer fund to ensure 
availability of cash to pay interest 
it also will play a role in drafting the national budget and 
debt policies and establishing accounting systems the report said 
it did not specify if the department will have authority to veto 
loans it considers unwise 
chinas foreign debt totaled about 168 billion at the end of 
last year the report said up from zero 10 years ago when the 
country began its drive to open its markets and absorb foreign 
technology 
although international debt experts still consider china a good 
risk chinese economists have expressed concern over the lack of 
central control over borrowing 
three ministries including the ministry of finance two banks 
and 10 provinces have independent authority to borrow money 
directly from foreign banks and issue bonds in foreign currencies 
in an effort to stimulate development the government has given 
increasing autonomy to coastal cities and provinces to make their 
own economic decisions including foreign loans 
several companies have been unable to repay loans from foreign 
banks and have sought government assistance 
the china daily indicated the government is not seeking to cut 
back on foreign borrowing only to supervise it more closely 
it quoted the ministry of finance source as saying china expects 
to increase its foreign debt through 1990 but will borrow only to 
build key state projects 
communist party general secretary zhao ziyang was quoted as 
telling visiting irish president patrick hillery last week that 
chinas slow growth in past decades was due to reluctance to borrow 
he said chinas principles are to borrow only for potentially 
profitable projects and to take careful account of the borrowers 
debtservicing ability the newspaper said 
</TEXT>
