<TEXT>
democrats and republicans have yet to 
nominate their parties standardbearers this november but 15 
modernday betsy rosses are embroidering the flags that will 
accompany the new president who will take office next january 
in the basement of building 13 of the defense departments 
supply center below the gymnasiumsized rooms where huge spools of 
olive drab thread turn into acres of us army fatigues the women 
of the embroidering room serve the next president with needles in 
hand and thimbles on fingers 
beyond the whine of sewing machines behind the cinder block 
walls the basement of building 13 is the only place in the country 
where the presidents flags are made 
tiny spots of chalk dust outline the eagle and stars that make 
up the presidents coat of arms as the women gently poke 19 colors 
of silk and synthetic threads through the navy blue rayon banner 
held taut across a wooden rack 
for the women in the embroidery room who spend most of their 
time embroidering detail on military units flags the opportunity 
to work on a flag for the president holds a special thrill 
when he talks on television i look at the seal said maria 
t negron who learned embroidery as a hobby while growing up in 
puerto rico 
the women embroider hundreds of flags each year for various 
military units cabinet members and congress but the presidential 
flag is most important the workers said 
we make sure all the employees get a chance to work on a 
presidential flag its one of the best morale builders said 
frank bennett production chief at the centers manufacturing 
directorate 
