<TEXT>
the steel industrys hardearned rebound 
is reviving the taconite mines of the mesabi iron range where 
skilled workers who were banished by layoffs years ago are suddenly 
in short supply 
the rare labor shortage has emerged as a call for help goes out 
to extaconite workers who fled as far away as arizona and florida 
during the industrys sevenyear recession 
they often are torn between remaining in their new jobs or 
returning to northeastern minnesota where family ties run as deep 
as the mine pits that helped fight two world wars by supplying ore 
to the nations steelmakers 
people want to come back home said tom gilpin placement 
interviewer for the minnesota department of jobs and training in 
virginia minn but i guess weve been burned so many times up 
here some of them just dont believe its going to last 
gilpin who is taking applications for jobs at ltv steel mining 
co in hoyt lakes said some former employees who were called back 
to work rejected the opportunity because they are secure in their 
new jobs but most miners some laid off for up to five years 
have returned 
im glad to see it said ed logan 32 of palo who was 
called back to work at ltv after being laid off nearly five years 
i didnt think id ever get called back but i guess i just kept 
hanging in 
logan said he eked out a living on the iron range working a 
variety of jobs during his extended layoff being single helped him 
avoid the fate of some of his married friends many of whom were 
forced to leave the area he said 
the decline of the taconite mines in recent years followed the 
slide in steel production taconite is a flintlike rock containing 
a lowgrade iron ore that is extracted and converted into pellets 
the pellets are then shipped to steel plants for smelting 
iron range taconite production peaked at 56 million tons in 
1979 and fell as low as 23 million tons in 1982 industry experts 
estimate 40 percent of the 25 billion worth of mining equipment 
in minnesota the nations largest producer of iron ore was idle 
in recent years 
taconite production in 1988 is projected at about 40 million 
tons up from 31 million tons in 1987 
al france executive director of the lake superior industrial 
bureau in duluth said the six working taconite plants on the iron 
range currently employ about 5000 people about 500 more than a 
year ago but well below the 1979 high of 15000 
eldon kirsch district 33 president of the united steelworkers 
of america in duluth said the rebound has been made possible by 
wage concessions and job consolidation 
its better now than it has been since 1980 kirsch said 
but that doesnt mean we have all our people back 
plants that operated with 500 in the past are operating with 
300 he added where there were 2000 workers now 1300 are 
employed 
most of the current hiring is taking place at the ltv plant in 
hoyt lakes where three shifts aim to produce 82 million tons of 
taconite pellets this year and at eveleth mines where a second 
production line is scheduled to begin july 1 after being idle since 
1982 
were wide open right now for the first time since 1976 
said jim kozar of ltv president of local 4108 of the united 
steelworkers of america 
kozar kirsch gilpin and others say there is an abundance of 
unskilled labor but a shortage of electricians with mining 
experience most iron range taconite producers ended apprenticeship 
programs for electricians in the downturn and many of the laidoff 
electricians have landed secure jobs in other places that they are 
afraid to leave they said 
were losing a certain number of them said bob raich 
personnel director at eveleth the supply of technical and craft 
people would be very very short right now if you were to start up 
a mining operation here 
kozar said the scaledback mining wage for electricians of about 
1150 an hour isnt helping to attract the top unexperienced 
electricians 
