<TEXT>
britains three leading sunday newspapers reported 
a serious split between prime minister margaret thatcher and her 
two most senior ministers over economic policy and said mrs 
thatcher was under party pressure to heal the reported rift 
aides to mrs thatcher deny there is a split and insist the 
prime minister has no plans to reorganize her cabinet the domestic 
news agency press association reported after the sunday telegraph 
sunday times and observer all headlined the alleged dispute 
the papers said mrs thatcher was in dispute with nigel lawson 
chancellor of the exchequer and foreign secretary sir geoffrey 
howe a former treasury chief over the strengthening british pound 
the pound has risen strongly since march arousing concern that 
the resulting higher prices of british exports would damage british 
business and industry 
the prime minister is opposed to further intervention to curb 
the pound on the grounds that it is inflationary lawson advocates 
a stable exchange rate interest rate manipulation and central bank 
intervention howe made clear last week that he favors british 
participation in the exchangerate stabilization of the european 
monetary system 
mrs thatcher is facing mounting pressure to move sir geoffrey 
howe from the post of foreign secretary if she cannot resolve her 
seemingly intractable dispute with him and mr lawsonover 
exchange rate policy said the sunday telegraph 
the sunday times which like the sunday telegraph usually 
supports the thatcher administration said senior members of the 
governing conservative party were pressing mrs thatcher and lawson 
to issue a statement denying there was a rift 
no formal statement emerged but press association quoted 
unidentified aides as expressing mrs thatchers determination to 
discount the reports of friction 
it also quoted unidentified government officials as saying any 
clear statement by the prime minister on exchange rate policy 
likely would help speculators and that government policy was to 
keep the speculators guessing 
the liberal observer said mrs thatcher was facing a damaging 
public row with howe and lawson it also said the dispute had 
renewed speculation that the cabinet may undergo a shakeup this 
fall and that lawson might resign before the next budget is 
unveiled also in the fall 
the telegraph took the unusual step of running a frontpage 
editorial saying the dispute was not a crisis or a conspiracy but a 
case of mismanagement that lies with mrs thatchers insensitive 
behavior 
it said she had a tendency to antagonize senior ministers and 
appealed to her to forget about being the iron lady for a change 
and start showing the human touch 
none of the papers attributed their reports but aides to senior 
ministers are known to brief the mass circulation sunday press 
extensively 
the telegraphs assistant editor bruce anderson wrote in his 
column that mrs thatcher and lawson have managed to heal their 
differences but that howe remained on the outside 
the newspaper cited howes comments last week suggesting britain 
should reconsider its reluctance to join the european monetary 
system a mechanism for stabilizing exchange rates mrs thatcher 
is known to oppose british membership 
last week howe reiterated britains intention to join the 
monetary system when the time is right but added we cannot 
forever go on adding that qualification to the underlying 
commitment 
anderson said that remark was bound to bring howe straight 
into controversy and said howe and mrs thatcher often were at 
odds on other foreign policy matters 
